<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> My Thoughts on SW (and a bit on WARS)<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.81)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=175'>Scott "CRingwell" Lingrell</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=175&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> August 26, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Some disclaimers:<br />
<br />
I am speaking, not you, not Company X or Company Y.  Not website X or website Y.   I am not an expert in everything I will list here (some things I am good at, some not) but will give my best opinion in making the following information available for everyone.<br />
<br />
An early PS  I have never offended anyone intentionally, nor wish that anyone that reads this thinks it is an attack/offensive/rude/etc.  For the record, I put $15,000 of my own money as a college student to run RamapoCon 3.  If thats not enough of a reason to know that I am selfless, you are beyond help.<br />
<br />
So I was thinking about Mike Carrs post about constructive criticism about SW: CCG and decided to discuss things that I would do in a perfect world to make a host of things different (hopefully better)in my opinionLook above for questions :).  I will try to write this loosely as an index for ease in reading.<br />
<br />
I. Star Wars CCG<br />
<br />
1. Prizes<br />
I now know they (Players Committee) are working on a tournament prize packages for any tournament what so ever allowing you to run events and always have prizes.  This is excellent for the community because it allows people to get cards they need still.<br />
		<br />
2. Ratings<br />
I know a lot of people were upset (or not) that their ratings were lost but I feel that the Decipher website is still an excellent place for ratings and tournament listings.  I feel that a new tournament-listing page should be made available (other than the tournaments listing on the PC site) with an easy format and listing of classic/open/fun/scenario/etc so people will know more information.<br />
		<br />
3. Player Locator<br />
Find out if people want to have a player locator.  You should get people to update their information correctly, with the email, city and first name (obviously privacy issues would be best just to have this stuff available) available so people know who to email when an event is scheduled.<br />
		<br />
4. Classic<br />
I loved the idea for classic, I even ran the test event at DCon 02 in VA Beach.  It was obviously broken without shields and was made better because of it. I know that with the limitation of not having every available non-episode 1 card does hurt the design of the tournament scenario.  <br />
<br />
If you can get the Classic Tournament Format to say: All Cards without an EP 1 icon are available, you would help the format grow.  To make it even better, have a qualifying event available in classic.  For example you have 2 open qualifiers on Sat/Sun with one being Open and the other being Classic.  People could be more involved.<br />
<br />
5. Large Events<br />
Call them DPCs, call them Mystic Visions 1K Event (which would help defer the cost of sponsorship  they could pay $250 to have it on all the promotional stuff, website, tournament listing, preferred retailer section, free banner ad, etc.  <br />
<br />
Here is a more detailed breakdown of how these events would work.  Here are what the guaranteed breakdown would be for each of these events (4 a year would be best). <br />
<br />
Winner $1,000  remember it should be guaranteed because they obviously bring more people.<br />
Second $200<br />
Third $100<br />
Fourth $100<br />
Four random $50 prizes  this makes it so anyone that plays can still win $50<br />
<br />
You charge $20 a head (which is $10 more than opens with much better prize support)<br />
<br />
You get 40 people; you raise $800 from people<br />
You get 50 people, $1000<br />
You get 60, $1200<br />
<br />
The rest of the $1600 would come from the other sources of income that include the store you are running it at, the local sub shop/pizza place for guaranteed shoppers, <br />
<br />
You could also do ad books ($25 an add, with local game shops, large companies, etc) or even talk to top websites put in some money for guaranteed rights to the decklists/constant updates, etc.  <br />
<br />
For example.  DeckTech gives $200 for each event.  Each event will have a writer that does nothing but do constant updates with scores, interviews, matchups, decklists, etc that are only on DT during the event.  That brings traffic like Metagame did for VS last weekend.  Make this part absolutely necessary for the events because everyone knows good coverage is hard to find.  <br />
<br />
		6. Websites<br />
First thing is first.  You need to make sure a website has the following things available for players new and old.<br />
-A Beginners section listing the best articles on how to build decks, meta, tournament play, sportsmanship, tracking, etc<br />
-A Section devoted to decks that list the best decks from different eras, formats and etc (not just a big clump of 5 start rated decks.) This way people old and new can click on 2004 Top 20 and see the best 20 decks from that year or the best Classic decks from 2005 or something.<br />
-An ask the expert question and answer section similar to what Lush did for SW and what Enrique does now with LOTR on DT.<br />
One of the websites needs to do a weekly/monthly radio program ala RFD or An Older Code because it works.  It generates interestI remember hearing my Sub Match versus Girard a few years back on AOC and it was a blast to remember what was playing.  With technology available, it is definitely possible to generate buzz and get people interested again easily.<br />
		<br />
7. Misc.<br />
Remember that when SW was played, people didnt play for the money or extravagant prizes.  Matt Sokol, Bastian, Matt Potter, Gary Carmen all got glass, free cards, and usually a plane trip and some free lunches.  But everyone else played and had fun regardless if it was a silly piece of plastic or an uncut sheet, you still had people fly in from everywhere to play.<br />
<br />
People that quit the game miss the game, you make it a guaranteed prize event and generate the buzz correctly, and people will come.  If you live one hour away from a big star wars event giving out $1,000, you are dang right you will try to show up, even if you have to beg or borrow cards that you dont have anymore.  Why not, you know the atmosphere will be worth it.<br />
<br />
II WARS TCG (any how it can relate to SWCCG)<br />
<br />
1. Prizes<br />
WARS will have some amazing prizes from what I read in giving away $10,000 and probably the usual cards/uncut sheets/signed artist stuff/foils. I think WARS from what I read is a great read so far and I like the artwork and the layouts of the cards.  The rules have been changed a bit but I havent played the games yet, so I have no idea of what it plays like.<br />
		<br />
		2. Player Locator<br />
With WARS players bringing old SW players out of the woodwork, this can only help people get more involved in gaming in general but also help get people get back into SW also.  Its like Yu-Gi-Oh being a gateway to gamers just like WARS will bring people to play both.  It can only help.<br />
<br />
3. Large Events<br />
Have 2 day events following the above format with day 1 being one game and day 2 being the other game (WARS, SW) with the winners getting the prizes above.  This will do two things, get people involved with both games and allowing decipher and the PC to work together again while promoting both games.  This = good for everyone.<br />
<br />
		4. Websites<br />
I remember when DeckTech first came on board.  It was a great chance to give players a place to write about decks, get feedback, etc.  I think by having DT and Decipher work together, if would be a great complement for both organizations.  You could have a WARS contest every month with articles, decks, trs winning cool prizes, cards, signed stuff, or even interviews on RFD or something.  <br />
<br />
I dont really need to go into too much detail here but I think each organization could allow each to grow much larger and also help the players out in the long run by having a great relationship.<br />
<br />
<br />
I think it would be the start to even bringing in other companies to work off the model set with those groups (for example DT and Decipher) like VS, Comic Images, etc.<br />
<br />
Well, my brain hurts but hope it was not too much reading.  I could get more detailed but I decided to cut it a bit short in some areas.<br />
